lays by Marlowe, Middleton, and Marston, Brustein investigates how Shakespeare’s contemporaries were preoccupied with similar themes and how these different artists treated the current prejudices in their own ways. Rather than confining Shakespeare to his age, this book has the wonderful quality of illuminating both what he shared with his time and what is unique about his approach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aMisogyny in literature. 0aPrejudices in literature. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aBuelow, George J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMann, Alfred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030011576540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015545740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300155457/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY